2026-06-14 | Exit Point in a Matrix

	Question
Find the exit point of the matrix.
	Key Insight
There are only four possible directions:
		0 → right
		1 → down
		2 → left
		3 → up
Whenever we encounter 1:
		dir = (dir + 1) % 4
and set the current cell to 0.
When we move outside the matrix,
the previous valid cell is the exit point.
	Approach
1.	Start at:
		row = 0
		col = 0
		dir = right
2.	While inside matrix:
		if mat[row][col] == 1
				dir = (dir + 1) % 4
				mat[row][col] = 0
3.	Move according to current direction.
4.	When indices go out of bounds:
		move one step back
		that position is the exit point.
5.	Return its coordinates.
	Time Complexity
	O(n × m)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> FindExitPoint(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int n = mat.size();
        int m = mat[0].size();
        int row = 0;
        int col = 0;
        int dir = 0; // 0:right, 1:down, 2:left, 3:up
        while(row >= 0 && row < n &&
              col >= 0 && col < m) {
            if(mat[row][col] == 1) {
                dir = (dir + 1) % 4;
                mat[row][col] = 0;
            }
            if(dir == 0) col++;
            else if(dir == 1) row++;
            else if(dir == 2) col--;
            else row--;
        }
        if(dir == 0) col--;
        else if(dir == 1) row--;
        else if(dir == 2) col++;
        else row++;
        return {row, col};
    }
};
	Key Insight
The direction changes only when a cell contains 1. By maintaining the current direction and simulating the movement exactly as described, the last valid cell before leaving the matrix is the required exit point.
